<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Environmental Audit Committee: Inquiry on Code for Sustainable Homes and the Housing Standards Review</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="font-size:13pt; line-height:115%; margin:10pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Cambria; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Centre for Sustainable Energy (CSE)</span></h2><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">About the Centre for Sustainable Energy and declaration of interests</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Centre for Sustainable Energy</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (CSE) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is an independent national charitable company </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">founded</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in 1979</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">work out of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Bristol</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> although much of our work has relevance and impact across the UK. Our clients and funders include national and local government and associated agencies, energy companies and charitable sources.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">At any one time, we have between 50 and 60 different and separately funded projects under way. All of these are helping people and communities to meet real needs for both environmentally sound and affordable energy services.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our charity’s vision is a world where sustainability is second nature, carbon emissions have been cut to safe levels and fuel poverty has been replaced by energy justice. Our mission is to share our knowledge and practical experience to empower people to change the way they think and act about energy. We believe in ‘low carbon localism’, including the ability for communities and local councils to set localised energy standards thereby driving local action on climate change, and we have supported several local authorities and community groups to develop a technical evidence base to underpin robust local policies on, for example, accelerated adoption of the Code for Sustainable Homes. Beyond this, and as an independent charity, we do not have any further interests to declare.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Further information including our board of trustees and details of projects we have run is on our website: </span><a href="http://www.cse.org.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">www.cse.org.uk</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Limitations of Building Regulations to deliver carbon reductions in new homes</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Technical Housing Standards Review Consultation’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Illustrative Technical Standards</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> proposes no additional standards for energy, with the wording </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“preferred option is to move towards a Building Regulations only approach”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The government’s aim is for new homes to be ‘zero carbon’ by 2016. Their definition means all emissions resulting from energy use calculated in building regulations must be zero-rated, either using on or off-site measures (‘Allowable Solutions’). This definition does not consider emissions from appliances or other energy uses not accounted for in Part L.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‘Transitional powers’, brought in for 2010 Building Regulations, have also weakened the ability for building regulations to drive sustainable construction. They allow all houses on a development site to be built to the same regulations, which are set at the time construction starts on the first home. Additionally, on purchasing the site a developer can apply for building regulations on the site up to a year before building. This has meant many new homes built are built to previous building regulations. This pattern will continue, unless these loopholes are closed. A method used previously was to apply building regulations at the time of construction for each individual building.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The latest tightening to Part L</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> will require a 6% reduction in CO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> emissions from homes built after April 2014, compared to 2010 standards. This reduction in carbon emissions is six months later than the Government proposed in their January 2012 consultation</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, and is substantially lower than their proposed 25% reduction. The previous two changes to Part L,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in 2006 and then again in 2010, both reduced regulated emissions by 25% compared to their predecessor. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Unlike the latest tightening to Part L, applying the Code for Sustainable Homes (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CfSH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">) Level 4 to new homes would deliver the government’s original proposed 25% CO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> reduction. This would require new homes to emit only 42% of the 2002 emissions, compared to 47% under building regulations. This would follow previous modelling used in developing UK carbon reduction strategy</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">When compared to 2002 emissions, the proposed 2016 tightening in Part L ‘carbon compliance’ represents CO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> emission reductions onsite of between 50% (low-rise apartments) to 70% (detached houses). This highlights that a large improvement on 2014 standards will be needed in 2016, given that current standards only achieve a 47% reduction</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This suggests there will be a large proportion of emissions developers will meet via Allowable Solutions when the zero-carbon homes standard is introduced. Developers will decide how to meet their requirements, not necessarily resulting in onsite renewable energy solutions</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Applying Code for Sustainable Homes Level 5-6 would put greater emphasis on onsite provision of renewable energy, which we believe is important to ensure new homes achieve as much viable carbon reductions onsite before looking at off-site solutions.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Government response to the “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Sustainable New Homes – The Road to Zero Carbon</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">” assumed an onsite carbon-reduction target of 70% of regulated emissions for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CfSH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Level 5-6 and zero-carbon </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">building regulations</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. We believe this is still an achievable target for larger developments to aim for, unless they can demonstrate it is unviable. Given that the government assumed this level in their response to the consultation, it is unclear why smaller non-detached homes will have a lower carbon compliance target. This consultation also proposed bringing in net zero carbon standards in 2016, in other words including unregulated emissions in the definition of the zero carbon homes. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We strongly believe Government is not revising Part L Building Regulations fast enough or far enough to meet UK carbon reduction targets, given the UK Carbon Plan assumes building regulations are bought in on-time and at a sufficient level to achieve ~70% carbon reductions onsite.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The benefits of setting localised energy standards and justification of how local authorities can fairly implement them</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">When setting localised energy standards for new homes, local authorities have been required to provide technical evidence that these standards can be achieved.  They are also required to consult on proposed policies to demonstrate they are widely supported for adoption in their area. A large number of local authorities have either already implemented them, or are considering implementing them through their local plans (previously known as local development frameworks). This represents a significant investment, which we conservatively estimate at around £4.8m by local councils to ensure that new homes achieve the highest viable sustainable energy standards</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Policies setting these standards typically allow construction even if the development cannot meet these standards, if the developer can prove meeting the policy requirements results in their development being unviable. The argument that local energy and sustainable construction standards put undue financial burden on developments appears non-applicable where local councils have included this caveat. CSE believes in this approach and recommends that the ability to set local energy standards should be retained.  Where viable, this allows for evidence-based insistence on better building standards, for the benefit of homeowners and communities.   Removing the ability of local authorities to insist on better standards, where viable, will almost certainly lead to the majority of new homes being built to the lowest standards mandated nationally.  The points made in (paragraphs 5-13 above) demonstrate why this will not deliver carbon savings quickly enough.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The viability of developments differs, depending on factors such as location, form and scale. Equally, the potential for achieving lower carbon emissions and higher sustainability standards will also vary between different forms and locations. The ability to assess this and, where there is a greater potential, set higher local energy standards will help improve the sustainability of new homes and ensure they meet local needs. This will also help meet UK carbon reduction targets faster than through a generalised, national, lower standard.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Broadly, local authorities have used several approaches to setting standards. The first and most prominent is through the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CfSH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, where the energy and CO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> category has the highest weighting. Some local authorities have chosen specifically these categories for developments to meet, whilst others have applied the whole standard. The consultation states: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">the government proposes to wind down the role of the Code”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (paragraph 40), without specifically consulting on this winding-down.  The Code itself is the result of significant consultation</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  A large amount of investment has occurred at the national and local level in delivering and improving the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CfSH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. As such, CSE believes it should not be dispensed with without due process of consultation. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CfSH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has significant benefits when compared to building regulations. Crucially, it considers factors building regulations do not, namely materials,  ecology and lifestyle (for example, including issues that make low-carbon living much simpler, such as cycle storage, home office spaces, and drying spaces). It also provides an easily enforceable planning policy, as developments can demonstrate they have achieved </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CfSH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> requirements by submitting their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CfSH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> design stage certificate carried out by an accredited assessor. Finally, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CfSH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> helps drive innovation in the materials and service supply chains by assessing developments’ sustainability on a sliding scale.  Its multi-themed approach makes it an excellent (and now well-understood) basis for continued improvements to the design and development of new homes, beyond 2016, which the Building Regulations regime is ill-designed to drive forward alone.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This consultation would significantly reduce or even eventually remove the implementation of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CfSH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Not only would this remove the independent framework for assessing new homes’ sustainability on a sliding scale, it would also hamper organisations who have invested heavily in being able to meet or assess homes’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CfSH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> requirements. The consequences of this would slow or even stall the development and training in low-carbon skills, resulting in the construction sector struggling to deliver zero-carbon homes in the future.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We do not believe the consultation or its impact assessment considers these issues. Our other concern with the impact assessment is the level of confidence put into the EC Harris study investigating ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">otential cost impacts – Summary’ of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CfSH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The study estimated </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CfSH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> costs through internal cost databases and informal consultations. CSE would recommend a more transparent study, looking at real-world developments and drawing from the learning of local authorities who have implemented </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CfSH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> via policy</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The second method local councils use to set localised energy standards is via setting ‘Merton Rule’ targets</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. These targets require a certain level of renewable energy generation onsite where viable, resulting in a percentage proportion of energy or carbon reduction. As with the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CfSH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, developers do not have to meet these standards if they can prove achieving them would result in their development being unviable to construct.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Where implemented, these targets would almost certainly help increase the local installed renewable energy capacity and develop the local renewable energy supply chain. In turn, this helps meet the UK renewable energy generation target of a 15% contribution of our energy from renewable sources in 2020. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Under Allowable Solutions proposals, developers will have the investment decision of which low-carbon offsetting schemes they wish to support. Local councils who have Merton Rule targets within their local planning policy will help ensure some of these benefits are realised locally, whilst still not prescribing to developers which technology or project to invest in. We believe these planning policies are complementary in the delivery of local benefits within Allowable Solutions.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Fundamentally, we believe in localism including greater local autonomy over planning policy and the local shaping of development. R</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">emoving </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ability of local authorities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to set evidence-based requirements for the delivery of high-quality housing in their area </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">goes against</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> everything that the Localism Act stands for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">t also erodes the impact of the flagship Community Rights and Neighbourhood Planning agendas that were designed to devolve such decision-making powers yet further.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Taking into account the resource that has gone into setting localised sustainable construction and energy standards, in conjunction with developers typically being provided a ‘where viable’ caveat to these requirements, CSE can see no purpose to removing them; apart from increasing profit-margins for developments that would have been viable, even if meeting localised standards.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Examples of localised energy standards for new residential development</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A number of CSE’s previous projects have delivered local evidence-based studies to inform local authority planning policies, setting requirements for the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CfSH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and/or onsite renewable energy generation targets. We have summarised these below as evidence of councils properly applying local energy-related policies informed by local evidence.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CSE completed a renewable energy study for Plymouth City Council in 2007</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. The council used this to inform their core strategy</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, which requires all major new developments achieve a 15% CO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> reduction through incorporating renewable energy generation integrated into the development.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In 2009, CSE delivered the Bristol Citywide Sustainable Energy Study on behalf of Bristol City Council</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. This study led to their Core Strategy policies setting requirements for a 20% reduction in residual CO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> emissions (following Building Regulations and increased energy efficiency standards) from renewable energy sources and, from 2016, Code for Sustainable Homes Level 6 will be applied</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Following on from the establishment of those policies, CSE is now delivering an ‘energy strategy’ on behalf of Bristol City Council, for a major development area called the Temple Quarter Enterprise Zone. If the current consultation proposals are adopted, it is likely to result in a situation where Bristol City Council’s Core Strategy policies on localised energy and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CfSH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> requirements cannot be enforced.  As a result the strength and ability to deliver the energy strategy will be severely weakened.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Another CSE project completed in 2009 delivered a ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">West Sussex Sustainable Energy Study</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’ for West Sussex County Council</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Five district councils and one borough council have used this to inform the development of local policies on sustainable energy.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Adur</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> &amp; Worthing district council have used this in writing Revised Draft Policy 18-19 which requires an assessment for low carbon energy opportunities for major developments and sets </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CfSH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Level 4 for new development and BREEAM Domestic Refurbishment ‘Very Good’ standard for refurbishments to existing dwellings</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Mid Sussex District Council also used this study to inform their submitted District Plan</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Proposed local plan policy DP39 requires a 20% reduction in carbon emissions from on-site renewable energy sources, unless proven unviable by the developer. The CSE study also informed DP38, which sets sustainable construction standards for new homes of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CfSH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Level 4 prior to 2016, increasing to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CfSH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Level 5 for 2016 and beyond.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Arun</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> District Council also requires an onsite renewable energy contribution to residual energy requirements. Policy SP 18 requires major developments provide a 10% contribution, unless the developer can prove this is unviable for the development</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Horsham District Council used the CSE evidence-based study to inform their Planning Framework Preferred Strategy</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Draft Policy 36 requires new homes to achieve </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CfSH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Level 4, rising to Level 6 from 2016. Chichester District Council</span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> adopted similar requirements, albeit slightly lower </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CfSH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Level 5 requirement for new homes developed from 2016.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CSE have also developed local sustainable energy evidence-base studies for Teignbridge District Council</span><a name="_ftnref21"></a><a href="#_ftn21">[21]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Hinckley </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&amp;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Bosworth Borough Council</span><a name="_ftnref22"></a><a href="#_ftn22">[22]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Both of these studies were for use by these local councils to inform local planning policy, but have not yet resulted in the development of localised sustainable energy policy.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-indent:6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">3 October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Centre for Sustainable Energy, 3 St Peter’s Court, Bedminster, Bristol, BS3 4AQ.  0117 934 1400.  For further information about this submission, contact Kieran </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Highman</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">, Low Carbon Localism Project Manager. kieran.highman@cse.org.uk.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Changes to Part L of the Building Regulations, published 8 August 2013: </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/changes-to-part-l-of-the-building-regulations"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">www.gov.uk/government/publications/changes-to-part-l-of-the-building-regulations</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Consultation open 31 January to 27 April 2012: </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/government-takes-next-step-on-zero-carbon-homes--2"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">www.gov.uk/government/news/government-takes-next-step-on-zero-carbon-homes--2</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> The 2011 Carbon Plan sets the UK carbon reduction policy, superseding the previous 2009 Low Carbon Transition Plan: </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/policies/reducing-the-uk-s-greenhouse-gas-emissions-by-80-by-2050/supporting-pages/carbon-budgets"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">www.gov.uk/government/policies/reducing-the-uk-s-greenhouse-gas-emissions-by-80-by-2050/supporting-pages/carbon-budgets</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Consultation open 6 August to 15 October 2013: </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/next-steps-to-zero-carbon-homes-allowable-solutions"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">www.gov.uk/government/consultations/next-steps-to-zero-carbon-homes-allowable-solutions</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Code for sustainable homes and the energy efficiency standard for zero-carbon homes consultation: summary of responses</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> (November 2010): </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/code-for-sustainable-homes-and-the-energy-efficiency-standard-for-zero-carbon-homes"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">www.gov.uk/government/consultations/code-for-sustainable-homes-and-the-energy-efficiency-standard-for-zero-carbon-homes</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Based on 50% of the 320 local councils in England adopting a study, and CSEs experience of studies costing an average of £25,000 adding on £5,000 for local councils own staff time. 2012 NHBC research suggests approximately half of local councils have adopted a local renewable energy target: </span><a href="http://www.nhbc.co.uk/NewsandComment/Documents/filedownload,47340,en.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">www.nhbc.co.uk/NewsandComment/Documents/filedownload,47340,en.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Technical guides to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">CfSH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> were produced every year between 2006-2010. In addition to this consultation on the Technical Housing Standards Review, Government ran consultations in 2007 and 2010-11. Details of these can be found here: </span><a href="http://www.planningportal.gov.uk/buildingregulations/greenerbuildings/sustainablehomes/consultations"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">www.planningportal.gov.uk/buildingregulations/greenerbuildings/sustainablehomes/consultations</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn9"></a><a href="#_ftnref9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Such as Element Energy 2013 study on ‘Costs of building to the Code for Sustainable Homes’, which drew learning from 5 local authorities who have implemented </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">CfSH</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> via policy: </span><a href="http://www.brighton-hove.gov.uk/sites/brighton-hove.gov.uk/files/EP059%20Costs%20of%20building%20to%20the%20Code%20for%20Sustainable%20Homes%20(Sept%202013)%20(draft).pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">www.brighton-hove.gov.uk/sites/brighton-hove.gov.uk/files/EP059%20Costs%20of%20building%20to%20the%20Code%20for%20Sustainable%20Homes%20(Sept%202013)%20(draft).pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn10"></a><a href="#_ftnref10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> The Merton Rule was the first local planning policy to set a requirement for renewable energy generation in new buildings, developed by Merton Borough Council in 2003. The rule required any new residential development of more than 10 units, or any commercial building over 1,000m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, to generate at least 10% of its energy needs from on-site renewable energy equipment: </span><a href="http://www.merton.gov.uk/environment/planning/planningpolicy/mertonrule.htm"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">www.merton.gov.uk/environment/planning/planningpolicy/mertonrule.htm</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn11"></a><a href="#_ftnref11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Plymouth Renewable Energy Strategic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Viability Study </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">2007</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">): </span><a href="http://www.plymouth.gov.uk/homepage/environmentandplanning/planning/planningpolicy/ldf/ldfbackgroundreports.htm"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">www.plymouth.gov.uk/homepage/environmentandplanning/planning/planningpolicy/ldf/ldfbackgroundreports.htm</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn12"></a><a href="#_ftnref12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Plymouth Local Development Framework 2007, Chapter 11 Natural Environment: </span><a href="http://www.plymouth.gov.uk/core_strategy_4web_11_chapter_11.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">www.plymouth.gov.uk/core_strategy_4web_11_chapter_11.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn13"></a><a href="#_ftnref13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Report available to download here: </span><a href="http://www.bristol.gov.uk/page/bristol-citywide-sustainable-energy-study"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">www.bristol.gov.uk/page/bristol-citywide-sustainable-energy-study</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn14"></a><a href="#_ftnref14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Bristol City Council Core Strategy policies BCS14 and BCS15, adopted June 2011: </span><a href="http://www.bristol.gov.uk/page/planning-and-building-regulations/planning-core-strategy"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">www.bristol.gov.uk/page/planning-and-building-regulations/planning-core-strateg